Julie Furber: We'll give our customers what they need when they need it, rather than telling them what they need to have.
Brett Merritt reiterating that we believe in the power of choice.
Hearing from Scott Davis about the new joint venture with @Eaton. "It's just the start."
Question about waste heat recovery. Answer: payback is what helps customers decide.
Now for Q&A with Tracy Embree, Julie Furber and Srikanth Padmanabhan.
We are in long haul for the long haul.
Our next gen heavy-duty engine for 2022: more efficient, more powerful, smaller and lighter.
Excited about our new partnership with @eatoncorp: https://t.co/DF6Xg19xkv
We have been able to provide a very effective suite of products in 2017.
Cummins is the market leader in commercial vehicle powertrains globally.
We have implemented our ADEPT suite of software and will enhance it with features like predictive shifting and optimized power and safety.
Sensors, effective communication, and computing is helping autonomy come alive.
Regardless of power solution, Connected Customer Care will drive better business results for our customers.
By the end of the decade, every engine we ship globally will be an electronic engine, allowing us to provide the data our customers need.
Now, on to connectivity: the confluence of reliable hardware and "killer" apps that help customers do things they need to do.
We will be there to provide that power of choice for our customers, regardless of what the powertrain is going to be.
It's a pivotal time in our industry. Three main disruptions: 1) energy diversity 2) connectivity 3) automation.
@Cummins is bringing diversified, dependable technology solutions to our customers. We understand power for our customers.
It is the customer that matters to us.
We've done it before, and we'll do it again.
When the industry changes or technology changes, we deliver.
We'll hear from Srikanth Padmanabhan, President of the Engine business.
By powering a world that's always on, @Cummins is shaping the future of power solutions.

Thank you to Lyle Cummins for sharing the history of his father and Cummins founder, Clessie Cummins
1942 - Clessie begins supporting the War Production Board on behalf of the diesel industry.
1931 - Cummins begins making locomotive engines.
Nov. 1932 - Another trip across country from NYC to LA powered by the Model H.
Dec. 1931 - Clessie and team start a 14 day endurance run at the Indianapolis Motor Speedway. 13,535 miles non-stop.
Aug 1931 - Clessie and team travels from NYC to LA powered by the Model U. It took 127 hours and cost $11.22 for fuel.
1931 - Entered the Indy 500 and became the first car to complete the race without stopping for fuel.
Feb. 1930 - Clessie takes his Packard roadster to Daytona to test it at speed trials on the beach
1930 - Clessie travels from Indianapolis to NYC 792 miles with an average speed of 31.9 mph, 26.4 mpg and spent $1.38 on fuel for the trip
1927 - The Model U is built. The first totally enclose diesel engine.
1924 - 1,2,3 and 4 cylinder Model F engine is created. By 1927, it was used in every US Coast Guard lighthouse
1919 - Cummins Engine Company is started. He convinced shrimp boats to run on his new diesel engine.
1915 - Clessie had his first patent for a stuffing box to allow for prpeller shaft misalignment.
1911 - Clessie was on the pit crew of the first Indy 500 winner.
1910 - at age 22, Clessie began chauffeuring for the Irwin family driving his Packard car.
Lyle Cummins: 1903, Clessie Cummins built his first automobile
